to “make it new.” In her revisionist “micropoetics,” Perloff draws primarily on major modernist poets from Stein and Yeats to Beckett, suggesting that the usual emphasis on what this or that poem is “about,” does not do justice to its infrathin possibilities. From Goethe’s eight-line “Wanderer’s Night Song” to Eliot’s Four Quartets, to the minimalist lyric of Rae Armantrout, Infrathin is designed to challenge our current habits of reading and to answer the central question: what is it that makes poetry poetry?  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aPoetics. 0aPoetry. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aliterary, critic, visual, grammatical, sound, duchamp, objects, language, poetry, verse, prose, words, phrases, discourse, etymology, grammar, modernist, poets, stein, yeats, beckett, poem, goethe, eliot, minimalist, armantrout, micro-poetics, micro, poetics.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073919040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226712772423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226712772/original  a978-3-11-073919-0  University of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles